A non-scientific example workspace to showcase and test the loading and usage of .RData-files

Carlotta Workospacy

Institute for Geoinformatics, Westfälische Wilhelms-Universität Münster, Heisenbergstraße 2, 40149 Münster, Germany

07 June 2018

Abstract

Loading .RData files in a RMarkdown file is dead simple. Just how simple, you ask? The examples given below demonstrate just how simple working with .RData files is. The code featured in this workspace will load an example.RData file, containing the iris and mtcars datasets, which are included in R. It will then create a set of simple, yet colourful plots of the datasets respectively, seperated into a chunk of code for each dataset.

Load datasets and required libraries ‘ggplot2’ and ‘gplots’

library(ggplot2)
library(gplots)

load("example.RData")

Taken from https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/moac/people/students/peter_cock/r/iris_plots/ (07.06.2018).

Original sources:

mtcars

Henderson and Velleman (1981), Building multiple regression models interactively. Biometrics, 37, 391–411.

iris

Fisher, R. A. (1936) The use of multiple measurements in taxonomic problems. Annals of Eugenics, 7, Part II, 179–188.

The data were collected by Anderson, Edgar (1935). The irises of the Gaspe Peninsula, Bulletin of the American Iris Society, 59, 2–5.
